Большинство транзакций с биткойнами генерируют два выхода. Один - сумма для отправки получателю, а другой - сдача для возврата отправителю. Особенности создания транзакций большинством кошельков позволяют третьей стороне отслеживать блокчейн Bitcoin на предмет того, какая из этих двух сумм была отправлена принимающей стороне, и какая сумма была возвращена отправителю. Возвращенная отправителю сумма может быть позже использована в будущих сделках и для дальнейшего раскрытия сведений контролирующей стороне. 

Кошелек DGC принимает меры для затруднения идентификации направлений отправки этих двух сумм. Для пользователей DGC доступны две опции: 

1. Перемешивание: Рандомизируется порядок выхода каждой транзакции. Иногда сдача может отправляться первой, а иногда второй. Если вы доверяете разработчику приложения, то воспользуйтесь рекомендуемым вариантом. 

2. Детерминистский подход: существует общепринятый стандарт заказа выходов транзакций (именуемый BIP69). Используя стандартные кошельки с открытым исходным кодом, пользователи не должны волноваться о том, как разработчики приложения реализуют выходы. Так как это новый стандарт, он еще не реализован во многих кошельках. В результате, пока что в блокчейн можно увидеть, была ли отправлена транзакция из кошелька, который использует этот стандарт или нет.

Эта настройка регулирует взаимодействие приложения с блокчейнами (в отношении отправки/получения транзакций). В том, что касается Bitcoin, Bitcoin Cash, Litecoin и Dash, она полностью одноранговая. Приложение пингует многие узлы и связывается с ними. Потенциально эти узлы могут регистрировать IP-адрес и запрашиваемые данные. Однако поскольку они выбираются случайным образом, каждый раз приложение подключается к новому узлу. 

В случае с Ethereum, мобильные кошельки не располагают альтернативным вариантом для взаимодействия с блокчейном, кроме как через сторонних поставщиков (например, Infura.io) или личные узлы Ethereum. Сторонние сервисы потенциально могут регистрировать IP-адреса и сделанные запросы. Эта информация может отображать местоположение, баланс, транзакции и т.д. Более того, кошелек должен быть уверен в достоверности возвращаемой информации. Существует альтернативный вариант, известный под именем Incubed, который, по сути, представляет собой сеть специальных узлов Ethereum. Эти узлы также могут регистрировать IP-адреса и сделанные запросы, но каждый раз они выбираются случайным образом. Хотя Incubed работает немного медленнее, чем Infura, он гарантирует достоверность возвращаемой информации (предотвращая фальсификацию данных). 

Другие блокчейны наподобие EOSIO и Binance Chain на данный момент являются исключительно централизованными средствами подключения, без эффективных альтернатив. Потенциально они могут регистрировать IP-адреса и сделанные запросы.

На данный момент у такого мобильного кошелька, как Unstoppable, есть два возможных способа для реализации этого вопроса: 

1. С сервера API: существует предопределенный сторонний сервер, на котором размещается вся цепочка блоков, происходит обработка всех данных и их подготовка к быстрому предоставлению. Это быстрый метод, однако он предполагает потенциальное отслеживание IP-адресов и запрашиваемых данных. Этот вариант рекомендуется использовать из-за скорости получения данных (5-10 минут). Он сопряжен с минимальными рисками. Если пользователь восстанавливает данные со своего собственного сервера, то нет никакой угрозы конфиденциальности. 

2. Из блокчейна: в этом случае приложение пытается восстановить данные напрямую из p2p-сети узлов блокчейна. Приложение пингует многие из этих узлов и запрашивает у них данные. Потенциально эти узлы могут отслеживать IP-адрес пользователя и сделанные запросы, однако во время восстановления данных приложение может переключаться между узлами. В любое время в сети находится около 10 000 биткойн-узлов. Это медленный вариант обработки данных, она может занять 2-3 часа и приложение должно быть открыто во время их восстановления...

Кошелек DGC предназначен для тех, кто хочет инвестировать и хранить криптовалюты частным и независимым образом. 

Это некастодиальный децентрализованный кошелек, в котором только пользователь может контролировать свои средства. Кошелек не собирает какие-либо данные и позволяет пользователю сохранять независимость, не завязывая учетную запись под одно приложение-кошелек. 

Кошелек DGC имеет открытый исходный программный код, и любой может убедиться в том, что приложение работает должным образом. 

Мы создали кошелек DGC для себя, так как доступные в сети решения не предлагают необходимый функционал на должном уровне. С точки зрения инженерии и простоты использования, мы считаем, что этот кошелек значительно опережает альтернативные продукты.
Я зашел в раздел \"Академия\" в этом приложении и ознакомился с базовыми аспектами хранения криптовалют.
Я создал резервную копию приватного ключа (-ей) для своих кошельков, показанных мне в виде 12-24 слов. Я понимаю, что эти приватные ключи хранятся на моем смартфоне, а не в другом месте.
Я понимаю, что передача моего телефона ненадежным лицам и отсутствие безопасной блокировки кошелька с помощью PIN-кода может поставить под угрозу безопасность моих средств.
Я понимаю, что джейлбрейк (или рутинг) моего телефона, установка приложений из неизвестных источников и устаревшая операционная система могут поставить под угрозу безопасность моих средств.
Я понимаю, что в коде этого кошелька могут быть не обнаруженные проблемы с программным обеспечением, что может привести к неожиданному поведению или сбоям в работе приложения.

Below you will find detailed explanation of the privacy settings that are available in the app. It\'s safe to consider them as settings for those that require extensive privacy.

This setting controls the privacy level of user's transactions on Bitcoin, Bitcoin Cash and Litecoin blockchains. 

Most Bitcoin transactions generate two outputs. One output is the amount that goes to the receiver and the other is the change output that is returned to the sender. The way most wallets construct transactions makes it easy for a third party monitoring Bitcoin blockchain to understand which of the outputs went to the receiving party and which one was the change amount returned to the sender. The output returned to the sender can then be used in future transactions and further reveal the details to the monitoring party. 

Erium Wallet implements measures to makes it significantly harder to figure out which output goes where. There are two options available to DGC users: 

1. Shuffle : The order of transaction outputs are randomized on every transaction. Sometimes change can be the first output, sometimes it can be the second. If a user trusts the developer of the app, than consider this a recommended option. 

2. Deterministic : There is a commonly agreed standard for ordering transaction outputs (known as BIP69). In open source wallets that standard ensures that wallet users do not need to trust how developers of the app implement the ordering of the outputs. As this standard is new, not many wallets have implemented it yet. As a result, it's somewhat possible to see on the blockchain whether transaction was sent from the wallet that uses that standard or not.

This setting controls how this app interacts with blockchains (sending/receiving transactions). In case of Bitcoin, Bitcoin Cash, Litecoin and Dash it is fully peer to peer. The app pings many nodes and communicates with them. Potentially these nodes can record IP address and data requested but since they are chosen randomly, each time the app connects to a different node. 

In case of Ethereum, there is no alternative for mobile wallets to interact with blockchain other than via third party providers (i.e. Infura.io) or personal Ethereum nodes. Third party services can potentially record IP addresses and the requests made. That info can reveal location, balance, transactions etc. Moreover, the wallet has to trust that information returned is correct. There is a an alternative known as Incubed which in essence is a network of special Ethereum nodes. These nodes can also record IP addresses and requests made, but they are chosen randomly each time. While being slightly slower than Infura, the way Incubed works pretty much guarantees that the information returned is correct (not fake). 

When it comes to other blockchains like EOSIO and Binance Chain, at this point they only provide centralized means of connecting, without viable alternatives. Potentially they can be recording IP addresses and requests made.

This setting is only relevant when restoring an existing wallet. It is a process of getting transactions history for a given coin so that the wallet app is able to display past transactions and calculate user's balance. This needs to happen only once, when user restores previously created wallet. At this point there are two potential ways for a mobile wallet like DGC to do this: 

1. from API Server : There is a third-party predefined server which hosts the entire blockchain and has all the data processed and ready to provide it in a fast manner. This method is fast but can potentially keep track of the IP addresses and the data requested. This option is recommended due to its speed of getting data (5-10 minutes). The risks are minimal. If the user restoring from his own server then no privacy risks at all. 

2. from Blockchain : In this case the app tries to restore directly from a p2p network of the blockchain nodes. The app pings many of those nodes and requests data from them. Potentially these nodes can keep track of user's IP address and requests made however during restore the app can switch between nodes. There are close to 10,000 Bitcoin nodes on the network at any given time. This option is slow and can easily take 2-3 hours, app needs to be open while restore is happening...

Below you will find detailed explanation of the privacy settings that are available in the app. It\'s safe to consider them as settings for those that require extensive privacy.

This setting controls the privacy level of user's transactions on Bitcoin, Bitcoin Cash and Litecoin blockchains. 

Most Bitcoin transactions generate two outputs. One output is the amount that goes to the receiver and the other is the change output that is returned to the sender. The way most wallets construct transactions makes it easy for a third party monitoring Bitcoin blockchain to understand which of the outputs went to the receiving party and which one was the change amount returned to the sender. The output returned to the sender can then be used in future transactions and further reveal the details to the monitoring party. 

Erium Wallet implements measures to makes it significantly harder to figure out which output goes where. There are two options available to DGC users: 

1. Shuffle : The order of transaction outputs are randomized on every transaction. Sometimes change can be the first output, sometimes it can be the second. If a user trusts the developer of the app, than consider this a recommended option. 

2. Deterministic : There is a commonly agreed standard for ordering transaction outputs (known as BIP69). In open source wallets that standard ensures that wallet users do not need to trust how developers of the app implement the ordering of the outputs. As this standard is new, not many wallets have implemented it yet. As a result, it's somewhat possible to see on the blockchain whether transaction was sent from the wallet that uses that standard or not.

This setting controls how this app interacts with blockchains (sending/receiving transactions). In case of Bitcoin, Bitcoin Cash, Litecoin and Dash it is fully peer to peer. The app pings many nodes and communicates with them. Potentially these nodes can record IP address and data requested but since they are chosen randomly, each time the app connects to a different node. 

In case of Ethereum, there is no alternative for mobile wallets to interact with blockchain other than via third party providers (i.e. Infura.io) or personal Ethereum nodes. Third party services can potentially record IP addresses and the requests made. That info can reveal location, balance, transactions etc. Moreover, the wallet has to trust that information returned is correct. There is a an alternative known as Incubed which in essence is a network of special Ethereum nodes. These nodes can also record IP addresses and requests made, but they are chosen randomly each time. While being slightly slower than Infura, the way Incubed works pretty much guarantees that the information returned is correct (not fake). 

When it comes to other blockchains like EOSIO and Binance Chain, at this point they only provide centralized means of connecting, without viable alternatives. Potentially they can be recording IP addresses and requests made.

This setting is only relevant when restoring an existing wallet. It is a process of getting transactions history for a given coin so that the wallet app is able to display past transactions and calculate user's balance. This needs to happen only once, when user restores previously created wallet. At this point there are two potential ways for a mobile wallet like DGC to do this: 

1. from API Server : There is a third-party predefined server which hosts the entire blockchain and has all the data processed and ready to provide it in a fast manner. This method is fast but can potentially keep track of the IP addresses and the data requested. This option is recommended due to its speed of getting data (5-10 minutes). The risks are minimal. If the user restoring from his own server then no privacy risks at all. 

2. from Blockchain : In this case the app tries to restore directly from a p2p network of the blockchain nodes. The app pings many of those nodes and requests data from them. Potentially these nodes can keep track of user's IP address and requests made however during restore the app can switch between nodes. There are close to 10,000 Bitcoin nodes on the network at any given time. This option is slow and can easily take 2-3 hours, app needs to be open while restore is happening...

This setting controls the privacy level of user's transactions on Bitcoin, Bitcoin Cash and Litecoin blockchains. 

Most Bitcoin transactions generate two outputs. One output is the amount that goes to the receiver and the other is the change output that is returned to the sender. The way most wallets construct transactions makes it easy for a third party monitoring Bitcoin blockchain to understand which of the outputs went to the receiving party and which one was the change amount returned to the sender. The output returned to the sender can then be used in future transactions and further reveal the details to the monitoring party. 

Erium Wallet implements measures to makes it significantly harder to figure out which output goes where. There are two options available to DGC users: 

1. Shuffle : The order of transaction outputs are randomized on every transaction. Sometimes change can be the first output, sometimes it can be the second. If a user trusts the developer of the app, than consider this a recommended option. 

2. Deterministic : There is a commonly agreed standard for ordering transaction outputs (known as BIP69). In open source wallets that standard ensures that wallet users do not need to trust how developers of the app implement the ordering of the outputs. As this standard is new, not many wallets have implemented it yet. As a result, it's somewhat possible to see on the blockchain whether transaction was sent from the wallet that uses that standard or not.

This setting controls how this app interacts with blockchains (sending/receiving transactions). In case of Bitcoin, Bitcoin Cash, Litecoin and Dash it is fully peer to peer. The app pings many nodes and communicates with them. Potentially these nodes can record IP address and data requested but since they are chosen randomly, each time the app connects to a different node. 

In case of Ethereum, there is no alternative for mobile wallets to interact with blockchain other than via third party providers (i.e. Infura.io) or personal Ethereum nodes. Third party services can potentially record IP addresses and the requests made. That info can reveal location, balance, transactions etc. Moreover, the wallet has to trust that information returned is correct. There is a an alternative known as Incubed which in essence is a network of special Ethereum nodes. These nodes can also record IP addresses and requests made, but they are chosen randomly each time. While being slightly slower than Infura, the way Incubed works pretty much guarantees that the information returned is correct (not fake). 

When it comes to other blockchains like EOSIO and Binance Chain, at this point they only provide centralized means of connecting, without viable alternatives. Potentially they can be recording IP addresses and requests made.

This setting is only relevant when restoring an existing wallet. It is a process of getting transactions history for a given coin so that the wallet app is able to display past transactions and calculate user's balance. This needs to happen only once, when user restores previously created wallet. At this point there are two potential ways for a mobile wallet like DGC to do this: 

1. from API Server : There is a third-party predefined server which hosts the entire blockchain and has all the data processed and ready to provide it in a fast manner. This method is fast but can potentially keep track of the IP addresses and the data requested. This option is recommended due to its speed of getting data (5-10 minutes). The risks are minimal. If the user restoring from his own server then no privacy risks at all. 

2. from Blockchain : In this case the app tries to restore directly from a p2p network of the blockchain nodes. The app pings many of those nodes and requests data from them. Potentially these nodes can keep track of user's IP address and requests made however during restore the app can switch between nodes. There are close to 10,000 Bitcoin nodes on the network at any given time. This option is slow and can easily take 2-3 hours, app needs to be open while restore is happening...

Below you will find detailed explanation of the privacy settings that are available in the app. It\'s safe to consider them as settings for those that require extensive privacy.

This setting controls the privacy level of user's transactions on Bitcoin, Bitcoin Cash and Litecoin blockchains. 

Most Bitcoin transactions generate two outputs. One output is the amount that goes to the receiver and the other is the change output that is returned to the sender. The way most wallets construct transactions makes it easy for a third party monitoring Bitcoin blockchain to understand which of the outputs went to the receiving party and which one was the change amount returned to the sender. The output returned to the sender can then be used in future transactions and further reveal the details to the monitoring party. 

Erium Wallet implements measures to makes it significantly harder to figure out which output goes where. There are two options available to DGC users: 

1. Shuffle : The order of transaction outputs are randomized on every transaction. Sometimes change can be the first output, sometimes it can be the second. If a user trusts the developer of the app, than consider this a recommended option. 

2. Deterministic : There is a commonly agreed standard for ordering transaction outputs (known as BIP69). In open source wallets that standard ensures that wallet users do not need to trust how developers of the app implement the ordering of the outputs. As this standard is new, not many wallets have implemented it yet. As a result, it's somewhat possible to see on the blockchain whether transaction was sent from the wallet that uses that standard or not.

This setting controls how this app interacts with blockchains (sending/receiving transactions). In case of Bitcoin, Bitcoin Cash, Litecoin and Dash it is fully peer to peer. The app pings many nodes and communicates with them. Potentially these nodes can record IP address and data requested but since they are chosen randomly, each time the app connects to a different node. 

In case of Ethereum, there is no alternative for mobile wallets to interact with blockchain other than via third party providers (i.e. Infura.io) or personal Ethereum nodes. Third party services can potentially record IP addresses and the requests made. That info can reveal location, balance, transactions etc. Moreover, the wallet has to trust that information returned is correct. There is a an alternative known as Incubed which in essence is a network of special Ethereum nodes. These nodes can also record IP addresses and requests made, but they are chosen randomly each time. While being slightly slower than Infura, the way Incubed works pretty much guarantees that the information returned is correct (not fake). 

When it comes to other blockchains like EOSIO and Binance Chain, at this point they only provide centralized means of connecting, without viable alternatives. Potentially they can be recording IP addresses and requests made.

This setting is only relevant when restoring an existing wallet. It is a process of getting transactions history for a given coin so that the wallet app is able to display past transactions and calculate user's balance. This needs to happen only once, when user restores previously created wallet. At this point there are two potential ways for a mobile wallet like DGC to do this: 

1. from API Server : There is a third-party predefined server which hosts the entire blockchain and has all the data processed and ready to provide it in a fast manner. This method is fast but can potentially keep track of the IP addresses and the data requested. This option is recommended due to its speed of getting data (5-10 minutes). The risks are minimal. If the user restoring from his own server then no privacy risks at all. 

2. from Blockchain : In this case the app tries to restore directly from a p2p network of the blockchain nodes. The app pings many of those nodes and requests data from them. Potentially these nodes can keep track of user's IP address and requests made however during restore the app can switch between nodes. There are close to 10,000 Bitcoin nodes on the network at any given time. This option is slow and can easily take 2-3 hours, app needs to be open while restore is happening...

Below you will find detailed explanation of the privacy settings that are available in the app. It\'s safe to consider them as settings for those that require extensive privacy.

This setting controls the privacy level of user's transactions on Bitcoin, Bitcoin Cash and Litecoin blockchains. 

Most Bitcoin transactions generate two outputs. One output is the amount that goes to the receiver and the other is the change output that is returned to the sender. The way most wallets construct transactions makes it easy for a third party monitoring Bitcoin blockchain to understand which of the outputs went to the receiving party and which one was the change amount returned to the sender. The output returned to the sender can then be used in future transactions and further reveal the details to the monitoring party. 

Erium Wallet implements measures to makes it significantly harder to figure out which output goes where. There are two options available to DGC users: 

1. Shuffle : The order of transaction outputs are randomized on every transaction. Sometimes change can be the first output, sometimes it can be the second. If a user trusts the developer of the app, than consider this a recommended option. 

2. Deterministic : There is a commonly agreed standard for ordering transaction outputs (known as BIP69). In open source wallets that standard ensures that wallet users do not need to trust how developers of the app implement the ordering of the outputs. As this standard is new, not many wallets have implemented it yet. As a result, it's somewhat possible to see on the blockchain whether transaction was sent from the wallet that uses that standard or not.

This setting controls how this app interacts with blockchains (sending/receiving transactions). In case of Bitcoin, Bitcoin Cash, Litecoin and Dash it is fully peer to peer. The app pings many nodes and communicates with them. Potentially these nodes can record IP address and data requested but since they are chosen randomly, each time the app connects to a different node. 

In case of Ethereum, there is no alternative for mobile wallets to interact with blockchain other than via third party providers (i.e. Infura.io) or personal Ethereum nodes. Third party services can potentially record IP addresses and the requests made. That info can reveal location, balance, transactions etc. Moreover, the wallet has to trust that information returned is correct. There is a an alternative known as Incubed which in essence is a network of special Ethereum nodes. These nodes can also record IP addresses and requests made, but they are chosen randomly each time. While being slightly slower than Infura, the way Incubed works pretty much guarantees that the information returned is correct (not fake). 

When it comes to other blockchains like EOSIO and Binance Chain, at this point they only provide centralized means of connecting, without viable alternatives. Potentially they can be recording IP addresses and requests made.

This setting is only relevant when restoring an existing wallet. It is a process of getting transactions history for a given coin so that the wallet app is able to display past transactions and calculate user's balance. This needs to happen only once, when user restores previously created wallet. At this point there are two potential ways for a mobile wallet like DGC to do this: 

1. from API Server : There is a third-party predefined server which hosts the entire blockchain and has all the data processed and ready to provide it in a fast manner. This method is fast but can potentially keep track of the IP addresses and the data requested. This option is recommended due to its speed of getting data (5-10 minutes). The risks are minimal. If the user restoring from his own server then no privacy risks at all. 

2. from Blockchain : In this case the app tries to restore directly from a p2p network of the blockchain nodes. The app pings many of those nodes and requests data from them. Potentially these nodes can keep track of user's IP address and requests made however during restore the app can switch between nodes. There are close to 10,000 Bitcoin nodes on the network at any given time. This option is slow and can easily take 2-3 hours, app needs to be open while restore is happening...

Sowohl bei der Bitcoin- als auch bei der Ethereum-Blockchain müssen Benutzer Nutzungsgebühren zahlen, wenn sie Transaktionen auf der Blockchain durchführen.\n\nDGC verwendet öffentliche Gebührenschätzungsdienste, um dem Benutzer zu helfen, angemessene Transaktionsgebühren für den Moment zu bestimmen. Die Auswahl eines Wertes aus diesem Bereich kann dazu führen, dass die Transaktion für mehrere Stunden aussteht oder ganz abgelehnt wird. Je niedriger der Wert, desto länger dauert es, bis die Transaktion bestätigt wird.
Typischerweise sollte diese Gebührenspanne ausreichen, um eine Transaktion innerhalb von Minuten/Stunde für Bitcoin und innerhalb von Minuten für Ethereum zu verarbeiten.

Below you will find detailed explanation of the privacy settings that are available in the app. It\'s safe to consider them as settings for those that require extensive privacy.

This setting controls the privacy level of user's transactions on Bitcoin, Bitcoin Cash and Litecoin blockchains. 

Most Bitcoin transactions generate two outputs. One output is the amount that goes to the receiver and the other is the change output that is returned to the sender. The way most wallets construct transactions makes it easy for a third party monitoring Bitcoin blockchain to understand which of the outputs went to the receiving party and which one was the change amount returned to the sender. The output returned to the sender can then be used in future transactions and further reveal the details to the monitoring party. 

Erium Wallet implements measures to makes it significantly harder to figure out which output goes where. There are two options available to DGC users: 

1. Shuffle : The order of transaction outputs are randomized on every transaction. Sometimes change can be the first output, sometimes it can be the second. If a user trusts the developer of the app, than consider this a recommended option. 

2. Deterministic : There is a commonly agreed standard for ordering transaction outputs (known as BIP69). In open source wallets that standard ensures that wallet users do not need to trust how developers of the app implement the ordering of the outputs. As this standard is new, not many wallets have implemented it yet. As a result, it's somewhat possible to see on the blockchain whether transaction was sent from the wallet that uses that standard or not.

This setting controls how this app interacts with blockchains (sending/receiving transactions). In case of Bitcoin, Bitcoin Cash, Litecoin and Dash it is fully peer to peer. The app pings many nodes and communicates with them. Potentially these nodes can record IP address and data requested but since they are chosen randomly, each time the app connects to a different node. 

In case of Ethereum, there is no alternative for mobile wallets to interact with blockchain other than via third party providers (i.e. Infura.io) or personal Ethereum nodes. Third party services can potentially record IP addresses and the requests made. That info can reveal location, balance, transactions etc. Moreover, the wallet has to trust that information returned is correct. There is a an alternative known as Incubed which in essence is a network of special Ethereum nodes. These nodes can also record IP addresses and requests made, but they are chosen randomly each time. While being slightly slower than Infura, the way Incubed works pretty much guarantees that the information returned is correct (not fake). 

When it comes to other blockchains like EOSIO and Binance Chain, at this point they only provide centralized means of connecting, without viable alternatives. Potentially they can be recording IP addresses and requests made.

This setting is only relevant when restoring an existing wallet. It is a process of getting transactions history for a given coin so that the wallet app is able to display past transactions and calculate user's balance. This needs to happen only once, when user restores previously created wallet. At this point there are two potential ways for a mobile wallet like DGC to do this: 

1. from API Server : There is a third-party predefined server which hosts the entire blockchain and has all the data processed and ready to provide it in a fast manner. This method is fast but can potentially keep track of the IP addresses and the data requested. This option is recommended due to its speed of getting data (5-10 minutes). The risks are minimal. If the user restoring from his own server then no privacy risks at all. 

2. from Blockchain : In this case the app tries to restore directly from a p2p network of the blockchain nodes. The app pings many of those nodes and requests data from them. Potentially these nodes can keep track of user's IP address and requests made however during restore the app can switch between nodes. There are close to 10,000 Bitcoin nodes on the network at any given time. This option is slow and can easily take 2-3 hours, app needs to be open while restore is happening...

This setting controls the privacy level of user's transactions on Bitcoin, Bitcoin Cash and Litecoin blockchains. 

Most Bitcoin transactions generate two outputs. One output is the amount that goes to the receiver and the other is the change output that is returned to the sender. The way most wallets construct transactions makes it easy for a third party monitoring Bitcoin blockchain to understand which of the outputs went to the receiving party and which one was the change amount returned to the sender. The output returned to the sender can then be used in future transactions and further reveal the details to the monitoring party. 

Erium Wallet implements measures to makes it significantly harder to figure out which output goes where. There are two options available to DGC users: 

1. Shuffle : The order of transaction outputs are randomized on every transaction. Sometimes change can be the first output, sometimes it can be the second. If a user trusts the developer of the app, than consider this a recommended option. 

2. Deterministic : There is a commonly agreed standard for ordering transaction outputs (known as BIP69). In open source wallets that standard ensures that wallet users do not need to trust how developers of the app implement the ordering of the outputs. As this standard is new, not many wallets have implemented it yet. As a result, it's somewhat possible to see on the blockchain whether transaction was sent from the wallet that uses that standard or not.

This setting controls how this app interacts with blockchains (sending/receiving transactions). In case of Bitcoin, Bitcoin Cash, Litecoin and Dash it is fully peer to peer. The app pings many nodes and communicates with them. Potentially these nodes can record IP address and data requested but since they are chosen randomly, each time the app connects to a different node. 

In case of Ethereum, there is no alternative for mobile wallets to interact with blockchain other than via third party providers (i.e. Infura.io) or personal Ethereum nodes. Third party services can potentially record IP addresses and the requests made. That info can reveal location, balance, transactions etc. Moreover, the wallet has to trust that information returned is correct. There is a an alternative known as Incubed which in essence is a network of special Ethereum nodes. These nodes can also record IP addresses and requests made, but they are chosen randomly each time. While being slightly slower than Infura, the way Incubed works pretty much guarantees that the information returned is correct (not fake). 

When it comes to other blockchains like EOSIO and Binance Chain, at this point they only provide centralized means of connecting, without viable alternatives. Potentially they can be recording IP addresses and requests made.

This setting is only relevant when restoring an existing wallet. It is a process of getting transactions history for a given coin so that the wallet app is able to display past transactions and calculate user's balance. This needs to happen only once, when user restores previously created wallet. At this point there are two potential ways for a mobile wallet like DGC to do this: 

1. from API Server : There is a third-party predefined server which hosts the entire blockchain and has all the data processed and ready to provide it in a fast manner. This method is fast but can potentially keep track of the IP addresses and the data requested. This option is recommended due to its speed of getting data (5-10 minutes). The risks are minimal. If the user restoring from his own server then no privacy risks at all. 

2. from Blockchain : In this case the app tries to restore directly from a p2p network of the blockchain nodes. The app pings many of those nodes and requests data from them. Potentially these nodes can keep track of user's IP address and requests made however during restore the app can switch between nodes. There are close to 10,000 Bitcoin nodes on the network at any given time. This option is slow and can easily take 2-3 hours, app needs to be open while restore is happening...

Below you will find detailed explanation of the privacy settings that are available in the app. It\'s safe to consider them as settings for those that require extensive privacy.

This setting controls the privacy level of user's transactions on Bitcoin, Bitcoin Cash and Litecoin blockchains. 

Most Bitcoin transactions generate two outputs. One output is the amount that goes to the receiver and the other is the change output that is returned to the sender. The way most wallets construct transactions makes it easy for a third party monitoring Bitcoin blockchain to understand which of the outputs went to the receiving party and which one was the change amount returned to the sender. The output returned to the sender can then be used in future transactions and further reveal the details to the monitoring party. 

Erium Wallet implements measures to makes it significantly harder to figure out which output goes where. There are two options available to DGC users: 

1. Shuffle : The order of transaction outputs are randomized on every transaction. Sometimes change can be the first output, sometimes it can be the second. If a user trusts the developer of the app, than consider this a recommended option. 

2. Deterministic : There is a commonly agreed standard for ordering transaction outputs (known as BIP69). In open source wallets that standard ensures that wallet users do not need to trust how developers of the app implement the ordering of the outputs. As this standard is new, not many wallets have implemented it yet. As a result, it's somewhat possible to see on the blockchain whether transaction was sent from the wallet that uses that standard or not.

This setting controls how this app interacts with blockchains (sending/receiving transactions). In case of Bitcoin, Bitcoin Cash, Litecoin and Dash it is fully peer to peer. The app pings many nodes and communicates with them. Potentially these nodes can record IP address and data requested but since they are chosen randomly, each time the app connects to a different node. 

In case of Ethereum, there is no alternative for mobile wallets to interact with blockchain other than via third party providers (i.e. Infura.io) or personal Ethereum nodes. Third party services can potentially record IP addresses and the requests made. That info can reveal location, balance, transactions etc. Moreover, the wallet has to trust that information returned is correct. There is a an alternative known as Incubed which in essence is a network of special Ethereum nodes. These nodes can also record IP addresses and requests made, but they are chosen randomly each time. While being slightly slower than Infura, the way Incubed works pretty much guarantees that the information returned is correct (not fake). 

When it comes to other blockchains like EOSIO and Binance Chain, at this point they only provide centralized means of connecting, without viable alternatives. Potentially they can be recording IP addresses and requests made.

This setting is only relevant when restoring an existing wallet. It is a process of getting transactions history for a given coin so that the wallet app is able to display past transactions and calculate user's balance. This needs to happen only once, when user restores previously created wallet. At this point there are two potential ways for a mobile wallet like DGC to do this: 

1. from API Server : There is a third-party predefined server which hosts the entire blockchain and has all the data processed and ready to provide it in a fast manner. This method is fast but can potentially keep track of the IP addresses and the data requested. This option is recommended due to its speed of getting data (5-10 minutes). The risks are minimal. If the user restoring from his own server then no privacy risks at all. 

2. from Blockchain : In this case the app tries to restore directly from a p2p network of the blockchain nodes. The app pings many of those nodes and requests data from them. Potentially these nodes can keep track of user's IP address and requests made however during restore the app can switch between nodes. There are close to 10,000 Bitcoin nodes on the network at any given time. This option is slow and can easily take 2-3 hours, app needs to be open while restore is happening...
